    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1914-10-01T12:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1914-10-01T12:00:00-05:00" n="334"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d334">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 763.72/1023</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in China</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_RPS1"
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Reinsch</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <dateline>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">American Legation</hi>,<placeName>Peking</placeName>, <date
                        calendar="gregorian" when="1914-10-02T01:00:00+08:00">
                        <hi rend="italic">October 2, 1914, 1 a.m.</hi>
                    </date>
                    <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received October 1, 6.30 p m</hi>.] </dateline>
                <p rend="center">[Telegram]</p>
                <p>As the result of a long Cabinet meeting to-day Liang Tun Yen informs me that the
                    Chinese Government, while accepting in good, faith the assurances of Japan and
                    not intending to offer any opposition to her operations, is deeply concerned
                    over the proposed military occupation of the Shantung Railway west of Weihsien
                    fearing that such penetration into the interior away from the seat of war will
                    almost inevitably lead to incidents beyond its control threatening to force
                    China into hostilities. President Yuan will, therefore, through Minister
                        <persName corresp="#p_FSK1">Shah</persName> ask President <persName
                        corresp="#p_WTW1">Wilson</persName> to confer with the British Government as
                    to the possibility of prevailing upon. Japan to restrict her action to the
                    necessary field of belligerent operations. The seriousness of the situation is
                    generally felt here.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_RPS1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Reinsch</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
